context: The iconic department stores of New Zealand's three major centres are Smith & Caughey's (founded 1880), in New Zealand's most populous city, Auckland; Kirkcaldie & Stains (founded 1863) in the capital, Wellington; and Ballantynes (founded 1854) in New Zealand's second biggest city, Christchurch. These offer <a0_0><b5_0>high-end and luxury items<b5_0/><a0_0/>. Additionally, Arthur Barnett (1903) operates in <a1_0><b6_0>Dunedin<b6_0/><a1_0/>. H & J Smith is a small chain operating throughout <a3_0><b8_0>Southland<b8_0/><a3_0/> with a large flagship store in <a2_0><b7_0>Invercargill<b7_0/><a2_0/>. Farmers is a mid-range national chain of stores (originally a mail-order firm known as Laidlaw Leeds founded in <a4_0><b9_0>1909<b9_0/><a4_0/>). Historical department stores include DIC. Discount chains include The Warehouse, Kmart Australia, and the now-defunct DEKA.
